pathing:
Use hand-rolled grid A* over a boolean walkable[row][col] Uint8Array. Cell size 64px. Map is ~64x64 cells (4096x4096px world) with lane corridors, river crossing, and jungle.

GRID SETUP:
```ts
// shared/map.ts
export const CELL = 64;
export const COLS = 64;
export const ROWS = 64;
export const walkable = new Uint8Array(ROWS * COLS); // 1=passable, 0=blocked
function idx(col: number, row: number) { return row * COLS + col; }
```

A* (hand-rolled, no lib needed at this scale):
```ts
// pure function, called host-side only
function astar(from: {col:number,row:number}, to: {col:number,row:number}): Array<{col:number,row:number}> {
  // binary min-heap by f = g + h
  // h = Chebyshev distance (diagonal movement allowed)
  // store came_from as flat Int16Array[ROWS*COLS*2] col|row
  // early exit when node === to
  // return path as array of waypoints, NOT every cell
}
```
Path is cached per (fromCell, toCell) pair for one tick; invalidated when a blocker changes. At 80 entities that's up to 80 A* calls/tick at 15Hz host cadence — acceptable since the grid is small (4096 nodes). Use Chebyshev heuristic to allow diagonal steering.

SMOOTHING: After A* produces waypoint list, run a simple string-pull: walk from start, keep extending line-of-sight (Bresenham) to furthest visible node; only emit a waypoint when LoS breaks. Result is 3-8 waypoints per path instead of 40.

HERO CLICK-TO-MOVE: Client sends `moveTo:{wx,wy}` intent. Host snaps to nearest walkable cell, runs A*, stores path on the unit entity. Path is NOT in the snapshot; only the unit's current world position + velocity vector is broadcast.

CREEP LANE FOLLOWING: Precompute fixed lane waypoint arrays at map load (just 8-12 Vec2 world positions). Creeps advance to next waypoint when within 32px. Local avoidance (see movement) handles separation without replanning.

BLOCKERS: Trees, buildings, and river are static; encode at load time. Tower attacks don't change walkability. Barricades (if any) dirty the walkable grid and invalidate path cache for cells within a 3-cell radius of the change.

movement:
STEERING MODEL — velocity-based, not tween-based (unlike bomberman's grid tweens):
```ts
type UnitSim = {
  x: number; y: number;       // world px
  vx: number; vy: number;     // px/s
  speed: number;              // max px/s (hero ~180, creep ~120, projectile ~400)
  pathWaypoints: Vec2[];      // remaining string-pulled A* waypoints
  waypointIdx: number;
};

function steerUnit(u: UnitSim, dt: number): void {
  const target = u.pathWaypoints[u.waypointIdx];
  if (!target) { u.vx = 0; u.vy = 0; return; }
  const dx = target.x - u.x, dy = target.y - u.y;
  const dist = Math.sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy);
  if (dist < 8) { u.waypointIdx++; return; }    // arrival radius 8px
  // seek: desired = normalize(dx,dy) * speed
  const nx = dx/dist, ny = dy/dist;
  u.vx = Phaser.Math.Linear(u.vx, nx * u.speed, 0.25); // soft steering
  u.vy = Phaser.Math.Linear(u.vy, ny * u.speed, 0.25);
  u.x += u.vx * dt; u.y += u.vy * dt;
}
```

SEPARATION (Boid-style, host only):
```ts
// O(n²) is fine at n=80; no spatial hash needed
for (const a of units) {
  let sx=0, sy=0;
  for (const b of units) {
    if (a===b) continue;
    const dx=a.x-b.x, dy=a.y-b.y, d2=dx*dx+dy*dy;
    const minD = (a.radius+b.radius)*1.1;        // ~35px for creep
    if (d2 < minD*minD && d2 > 0.001) {
      const d = Math.sqrt(d2);
      sx += (dx/d)*(minD-d); sy += (dy/d)*(minD-d);
    }
  }
  a.x += sx * 0.4; a.y += sy * 0.4;             // push, not velocity
}
```
Separation runs after steering each tick. With 80 units the inner loop is 6400 iterations at 15Hz = ~96k ops/s — trivial.

MAX ENTITIES: Design cap 80 (10 heroes + 60 creeps + 10 projectiles/FX objects). Separation O(n²) stays cheap. If creeps ever spike past 80, partition the separation loop by team (allied creeps only repel each other, not enemies) cutting to 2×40²=3200.

CLIENT-SIDE: clients do NOT re-run steering. They lerp the display object toward the broadcast world position at ~10x speed — this hides 66ms snapshot jitter without physics divergence.

rendering:
DEPTH SORTING BY Y:
All unit sprites, buildings, and projectiles get `depth = y + zOffset`. For a 192px sprite centered at world y, use `setDepth(worldY + 96)`. Ground tiles get depth -10, terrain decorations 0, units 100–3000+, UI overlay 9000+. Phaser sorts within the same scene by depth automatically — no manual sortChildren call needed.

SPRITE POOLING:
```ts
class UnitPool {
  private pool: Phaser.GameObjects.Container[] = [];
  acquire(scene: Phaser.Scene): Phaser.GameObjects.Container {
    return this.pool.pop() ?? this.createNew(scene);
  }
  release(c: Phaser.GameObjects.Container): void {
    c.setVisible(false).setActive(false);
    this.pool.push(c);
  }
  private createNew(scene: Phaser.Scene): Phaser.GameObjects.Container {
    const shadow = scene.add.image(0, 20, 'shadow').setDisplaySize(48, 24);
    const sprite = scene.add.sprite(0, 0, 'warrior-blue', 0);
    const hpBg = scene.add.graphics();
    const hpFill = scene.add.graphics();
    return scene.add.container(0, 0, [shadow, sprite, hpBg, hpFill]).setDepth(0);
  }
}
```
Pool per unit type (warrior, archer, goblin-torch, etc). Pre-allocate 20 per type at scene init; pool expands on demand. On release, set visible=false and return to pool.

HEALTHBARS AS GRAPHICS (not DOM):
```ts
// Inside the container, drawn into hpBg/hpFill Graphics children:
function updateHpBar(hpFill: Phaser.GameObjects.Graphics, pct: number, teamColor: number): void {
  hpFill.clear();
  hpFill.fillStyle(teamColor, 1).fillRect(-24, -56, 48 * pct, 5);
}
// Only redraw when hp changes, not every frame.
```

CONTAINER LAYOUT PER UNIT:
- shadow: Image at (0, +20), displaySize 48x24, depth-0 within container
- sprite: Sprite at (0, -8), displaySize 96x96 (scaled from 192px source)
- hpBg: Graphics at (0,0), draws a 48×5 dark rect at (-24, -56)
- hpFill: Graphics at (0,0), draws the green/red fill
- nameTag: Text at (0, -68) only for heroes, fontSize 11px
Container depth = sprite.y (world), so as unit moves north depth decreases.

