SAFE RUNTIME FRAME DISCOVERY (avoid hardcoding wrong row counts):
```ts
// At load time, inspect the texture to discover actual frame counts:
function discoverRows(scene: Phaser.Scene, key: string, frameW: number, frameH: number): number {
  const tex = scene.textures.get(key);
  const src = tex.source[0];
  if (!src) return 0;
  return Math.floor(src.height / frameH);
}
function discoverCols(scene: Phaser.Scene, key: string, frameW: number): number {
  const tex = scene.textures.get(key);
  const src = tex.source[0];
  if (!src) return 0;
  return Math.floor(src.width / frameW);
}
// Then create named anims by row index, not hardcoded frame numbers:
function registerAnims(scene: Phaser.Scene, key: string, cols: number): void {
  const ANIM_ROWS: Array<{name:string; row:number; frameRate:number; repeat:number}> = [
    {name:`${key}-idle`,   row:0, frameRate:8,  repeat:-1},
    {name:`${key}-walk`,   row:1, frameRate:10, repeat:-1},
    {name:`${key}-attack`, row:2, frameRate:12, repeat:0},
    // add more rows as discovered
  ];
  for (const def of ANIM_ROWS) {
    const start = def.row * cols;
    const end = start + cols - 1;
    scene.anims.create({
      key: def.name,
      frames: scene.anims.generateFrameNumbers(key, {start, end}),
      frameRate: def.frameRate,
      repeat: def.repeat,
    });
  }
}
```
This is safe even if Pixel Frog updates the sheet — frame count is read from the actual texture size, not a constant.

camera:
FOLLOW HERO: Use the bomberman pattern — manual scroll with lerp, NOT `camera.startFollow()` + `camera.setBounds()`. setBounds in Phaser 4 still clamps based on unzoomed canvas dimensions, causing a zoom-dependent void gap at map edges (same bug documented in memory/Phaser4 camera bounds/zoom void). Manual clamping is the safe path:

```ts
private updateCamera(heroX: number, heroY: number): void {
  const cam = this.cameras.main;
  const hw = cam.width / (2 * cam.zoom);
  const hh = cam.height / (2 * cam.zoom);
  const MAP_W = COLS * CELL, MAP_H = ROWS * CELL;
  const cx = Phaser.Math.Clamp(heroX, hw, MAP_W - hw);
  const cy = Phaser.Math.Clamp(heroY, hh, MAP_H - hh);
  cam.setScroll(
    Phaser.Math.Linear(cam.scrollX, cx - hw, 0.12),
    Phaser.Math.Linear(cam.scrollY, cy - hh, 0.12),
  );
}
```

EDGE-PAN WITH MOUSE (spectator / dead hero):
```ts
// Run in update(), only when not following hero
const EDGE = 40;             // px from viewport edge
const PAN_SPEED = 400;       // px/s
const {x, y} = this.input.activePointer;
const {width: W, height: H} = this.scale;
let px = 0, py = 0;
if (x < EDGE)   px = -PAN_SPEED;
if (x > W-EDGE) px =  PAN_SPEED;
if (y < EDGE)   py = -PAN_SPEED;
if (y > H-EDGE) py =  PAN_SPEED;
if (px||py) cam.setScroll(cam.scrollX + px*(delta/1000), cam.scrollY + py*(delta/1000));
```

DRAG/SPACE PAN:
```ts
// Middle mouse or space+drag
this.input.on('pointermove', (ptr: Phaser.Input.Pointer) => {
  if (ptr.isDown && ptr.middleButtonDown()) {
    cam.setScroll(cam.scrollX - ptr.velocity.x/cam.zoom,
                  cam.scrollY - ptr.velocity.y/cam.zoom);
